        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> errors are always `error()` (or `assert()`).\n\nI strongly disagree. While I agree that a goal of ui2 should be to make `error()`s display nicer, `error()` should still only be for non-interactive errors (lua errors in user configs, logic/runtime errors in plugins, etc.). For stuff like user error, `nvim_echo(..., { err = true })` should be used (or `:echoerr`, I guess), since the `error()` stacktrace is *never* useful in these situations and would simply add noise to the pager.\n\n> `vim.notify` [...] will be very much deprecated when ui2 becomes default.\n\nNice, that should clear up a lot of confusion around which function to use.",
